label.name_singular: Ventana al Pasado/Window on the Past
label.name_plural: Ventana al Pasado/Window on the Past
label.description:
Ventana al pasado is a bilingual web-based research collection that links the Latino-related records located in ten New York State archival repositories. Ventana brings together collections documenting the New York’s Latino/Hispanic community, and makes them accessible to researchers all over the world.

Coordinated by the New York State Archives and Centro de Estudios Puertorriqueños, Ventana al pasado unites 94 collections and over 3,100 digital images that document the social, political, and cultural lives of New York’s Hispanic and Latino communities through the records of Hispanic/Latino community leaders and organizations, union members, politicians, artists, and others. Governmental records shed light on its role in issues such as affirmative action, immigration, and bilingual education. Included in the resource are photographs, letters, flyers, and other archival records that document the diverse experiences of Latino/Hispanic populations in New York State.

Together these materials tell the story of communities previously underrepresented in the historical record and trace their experiences in New York.

The New York State Archives partnered with seven other historical records repositories to create a virtual collection on New York State's Environmental History. This NEH funded project (October 2002 - September 2005) created Internet-accessible finding aids for 162 collections and over 3000 images focusing on the environmental history of Adirondack and Catskill parks, 1885-1990.

If no other standard identifier exists, use a local call number, control number, accession number, or barcode. Identify the institution associated with such locally derived numbers.

label.name: Appraisal job number
label.description: This field records the appraisal job number assigned to each series that undergoes archival appraisal. Job numbers consist of two parts separated by a dash (for example, 96-01). The first part records the last two digits of the year in which the appraisal was done. The second part is the sequential number of the job done during that year. Numbers are assigned by the staff member in charge of appraisal beginning for each year with the number 01. An asterisk following the job number (for example, 96-02*) indicates that the same series was appraised in another appraisal report. The job number of that second report should be entered into the COMMENTS field. A second entry for that same series should also appear in the RDR database. That second entry will show the second appraisal report number, followed by an asterisk, in its JOBNO field, and will have a reference to the first appraisal report in its COMMENTS field. This allows the two database entries for the same records series which was appraised twice to be cross-referenced. A similar approach should be followed if a series is appraised three or more times, so that there are separate database entries for each appraisal report number, with all entries fully cross-referenced.

This field differs from the RECD field in that that field is the date that the signed, paper REC-3 form is received (which is date stamped on the REC-3). Often, we don’t receive the signed REC-3 until the associated REC-5s have been finalized.

label.name: Status of request
label.description: status of request: P - currently being reviewed by staff or is awaiting review R - indicates that the RDR did not meet the minimum standards for review and that the RDR was returned to the agency. O - indicates that the RDR has been sent to the State Comptroller and the Attorney General for their review and approval. RDRs sent to the State Archivist or designee for approval are also considered out for review. I - indicates that a Records Disposition Authorization has been issued for this record series. The RDRNO field is also completed when a series has a status of issued. The date of approval will be entered into the DATEAPPRVD field. W - indicates that the RDR was withdrawn from the review and approval process by the agency. C - indicates that the agency or the State Archives has cancelled the authorization assigned to that series. S - indicates that the RDA has been superseded by another RDA.

label.name: Date
label.description: This element identifies and records the date(s) that pertain to the creation, assembly, accumulation, and/or maintenance and use of the materials being described.

label.name: Extent
label.description: This element indicates the extent and the physical nature of the materials being described.

label.name: Administrative/Biographical History Element
label.description: A description of the context in which the materials being described were created, assembled, and/or maintained is as important as the description of the materials themselves

label.name: Scope and Content
label.description: This element provides information about the nature of the materials and activities reflected in the unit being described to enable users to judge its potential relevance.

label.name: System of Arrangement
label.description: This element identifies the various aggregations of archival materials, their relationships, or the sequence of documents within them.

label.name: Conditions Governing Access
label.description: This element provides information about access restrictions due to the nature of the information in the materials being described, such as those imposed by the donor, by the repository, or by statutory/regulatory requirements.

label.name: Physical Access
label.description: This element provides information about access restrictions due to any physical characteristics or storage locations that limit, restrict, delay, or otherwise affect access to the materials being described.

label.name: Technical Access
label.description: This element provides information about access restrictions due to any technical requirements restrict or otherwise affect access to the materials being described, such as equipment or specific hardware/software required for use.

label.name: Conditions Governing Reproduction
label.description: This element identifies any restrictions on reproduction due to copyright or other reasons, as well as restrictions on further use of the materials being described, such as publication after access has been provided.

label.name: Languages and Scripts on the Material
label.description: This element identifies the language(s), script(s), and symbol systems employed in the materials being described, particularly as they may affect its use.

label.name: Other Finding Aids
label.description: This element identifies any other finding aids to the materials being described particularly if they are available to the user, and provides information about the form and content of those finding aids.

label.name: Existence and Location of Originals
label.description: This element indicates the existence, location, and availability of originals when the materials being described consist of copies, and the originals are not held by the repository

label.name: Existence and Location of Copies
label.description: This element indicates the existence, location, and availability of copies or other reproductions of the materials being described when they are available for use in an institution, or for loan or purchase, or available electronically. Do not mention copies in private hands or copies made for personal use.

label.name: Publication Note
label.description: This element identifies any publications that are about or are based on the use, study, or analysis of the materials being described.

label.name: Processing Information
label.description: Provide information about actions of the archivist, custodians, or creators of the records or conventions in the finding aid that may have an impact on a researcher’s interpretation of the records or understanding of the information provided in the finding aid. Actions and conventions include but are not limited to reconstruction of provenance, maintenance, reconstruction, or alteration of original order, devising titles for materials, weeding, and maintenance or provision of control numbers or container numbers.

label.name: Preferred Citation
label.description: Indicate the preferred style for the citation of the unit being described.

label.name: Custodial History
label.description: This element provides information on changes of ownership or custody of the material being described, from the time it left the possession of the creator until it was acquired by the repository that is significant for its authenticity, integrity, and interpretation.

label.name: Immediate Source of Acquisition
label.description: Record information about changes of ownership or custody of the materials being described that do not involve direct acquisition by the repository and that are significant for its authenticity, integrity, and interpretation in the Custodial History Element.

label.name: Appraisal, Destruction, and Scheduling Information
label.description: This element provides information about the rationale for appraisal decisions, destruction actions, and disposition schedules that are relevant to the understanding and use of the materials being described.

label.name: Accruals
label.description: This element informs the user of anticipated additions to the unit being described. An accrual is an acquisition of archival materials additional to that already in the custody of the repository.

label.name: General notes
label.description: Record, as needed, information not accommodated by any of the defined elements of description.

label.name: Conservation notes
label.description: Describe any specific conservation treatment.

label.name: Note
label.description: Notes for general schedule items.

label.name: Records Not Covered
label.description: Records not covered by general schedule item.

settings.setting:
NYSA Identifier is formed using information derived from the Source field: Repository acronym, accession number, box number, folder number, item number and page number. Use as much of the information that is available, that is unique to the item, and that is understood by repository staff as it relates to the item and the NYSA record series it is part of. Do not use the file format (.jpg, .tiff) in the string.
  • Repository, box, folder, and page should be abbreviated in order to keep the string from becoming too long.
  • Do not use spaces to separate characters, instead use an underscore in place of a space. Exceptions to this rule are the hyphens used in accession numbers and the dashes contained in original identifying schemes such as identification numbers on the original resource. In cases where dots are used between characters or numbers, use an underscore.
  • Identifiers for multiple, unnumbered items contained in the same box or folder can be made unique by using consecutive item numbers in order of the item’s appearance in the box or folder.
  • Do not use box and folder numbers that may be considered unstable or unreliable.

The name given to the resource.

Formal Title: If the formal Title is appropriate, then transcribe the title directly from the resource itself using the same punctuation that appears on the original source. The title should not end in a period.

Supplied Title: If the archivist supplies the title, make the Title as descriptive as possible. The Title should reflect the function, activity, subject, individuals or organization that was the basis of its creation or use.
